ing the latest in a series of strange phone calls from Edmund Carpenter in New York to discuss successive versions of his Canadian Notes & Queries piece on Marshall McLuhan. He falls to reminiscing and at one point says: "Marshall always reminded me of that passage in Boswell in which Boswell says that if you chanced to take shelter from a rain storm for a few minutes in Dr Johnson's company, you would come away convinced that you had just met the smartest man in the world. Marshall was like that too. Of course, if you spent an hour with Marshall, well, that was something quite different."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthors, Canadian (English)xDiariesx20th century. 0aAuthors, Canadian (English)xDiariesx21st century. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh1 aBusby, Brian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358825740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773588257423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773588257/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles